flowRoot.flowPara: A. Reasoning about pathway activation. Most pathway approaches make use of either the set (top panel) or graph (middle panel) of signaling
molecules to make statements about a possible activation.We aim to build consensus gene signatures of known pathway activation using
publicly available perturbation experiments, and then link those back to mutations in cancer, drug sensitivity, and patient survival.
B. Workflow of data curation and model building. (1) Finding and curation of 208 publicly available experiment series in the ArrayExpress
database, (2) Extracting a total of 556 perturbation experiments from series' raw data, (3) Performing QC metrics and discarding failures, (4)

Computing z-scores per experiment, (5) Using a multiple linear regression to fit genes responsive to all pathways simultaneously obtaining the z-coefficients matrix, (6) Assigning pathway scores using the coefficients matrix and basal expression data.

C. Structure of the perturbation-response model. For the multiple linear regression, we set the coefficients or perturbed pathways to 1 if a pathway was perturbed, 0 otherwise. In addition, EGFR perturbation also had MAPK and PI3K coefficients set, and TNFa had NFkB set.

D, E. Pathway recall on input experiments. The outer ring shows which pathway was perturbed in the experiments used, and the target of an outgoing edge a significant occrelation of the pathway being perturbed and a change in pathway activity inferred by our method (D) vs. Reactome GSEA (E). Occupied angle corresponds to the number of experiments. Connections only shown for p<10-4. For our method, the mean difference in assigned pathway activity scores between basal and perturbed condition per experiment is strongly correlated with the pathway that was perturbed, as indicated by the mountains on the outer ring. This implies that consensus response signatures built from multiple different conditions are able to recover perturbed pathways, which the pathway expression GSEA score is not.

F. Correlation of inferred pathway activity from our method in basal expression of TCGA non-cancerous tissue controls recapitulates known crosstalk and is similar to the connections obtained by perturbations.
